@@ What is a Persistent Volume (PV)?
=> PV is actual storage provided to Kubernetes.

@@ Storage can come from:
NFS, AWS EBS, Azure Disk, VMware vSAN, Ceph, Local Disk, SAN Storage

#####################################
@@ Create PV:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# vim pv.yml
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: pv-demo
spec:
  capacity:
    storage: 1Gi
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  hostPath:
    path: /data/pv-demo

@@ Apply:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl apply -f pv.yaml

@@ Verify:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl get pv

@@ Output:
pv-demo 1Gi Available


###############################
### Understanding Access Modes #3#

ReadWriteOnce (RWO)
One Node
Read + Write

Used by: MySQL, PostgreSQL, MariaDB


ReadOnlyMany (ROX)
Multiple Nodes
Read Only

Example: Shared Documentation

ReadWriteMany (RWX)
Multiple Nodes
Read + Write

Used with: NFS, CephFS, NetApp


###################################
@@ What is PVC?
=> Applications never use PV directly. Applications request storage using PVC.

@@ Think: 
Developer asks for storage (PVC)
Storage Team provides: (PV)

@@ Architecture

Developer
    |
  PVC
    |
   PV
    |
Storage Admin

############################
##### Create PVC #######
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# vim pvc.yml
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: app-pvc
spec:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 500Mi

@@ Apply:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl apply -f pvc.yml

@@ Verify:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl get pvc

@@ Output:
app-pvc Bound

@@ Check PV
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl get pv

@@ Output:
pv-demo Bound


#############################
##### Using PVC in Pod #####
@@ Create Pod:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# vim pod.yml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: pvc-demo
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
    volumeMounts:
    - name: data-volume
      mountPath: /data
  volumes:
  - name: data-volume
    persistentVolumeClaim:
      claimName: app-pvc

@@ Deploy:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]#  kubectl apply -f pod.yml

@@ Verify:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl exec -it pvc-demo -- bash

@@ Create file:
echo "Kubernetes Day12" > /data/test.txt

@@ Delete Pod:
[root@k8s-control01 ~]# kubectl delete pod pvc-demo

Recreate Pod.

@@ Check:
cat /data/test.txt

@@ Output:
Kubernetes Day12

@@ Lesson: Pod Deleted => Data Survives
This is the entire purpose of PV/PVC.


